      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "8ebe14b1817e7e78",
        "text": "In the aftermath of the global financial and economic crisis of 2007–2008, two separate albeit related developments contributed to an environment in which AI capitalism could emerge: a changing political context and a technological transformation.\n\nFirst, the broader political context has changed by what Standing (2016) calls a global transformation. Essentially, he refers to a shift in the political context from neoliberalism to rentier capitalism. Neoliberalism promotes free markets and includes other dynamics and characteristics, such as commodification, privatisation and labour market reregulation (not deregulation) in favour of flexibility in terms of labour and capital (Harvey 2005). Rentier capitalism, on the other hand, refers to a system in which efforts are made to enlarge one’s existing share of wealth without actually contributing to the creation of new wealth (Christophers 2020; Standing 2016). It constitutes a model of monopolistic rent-seeking, which often leads to markets dominated by a small number of extremely powerful multinationals (Birch 2020)."
